=========================================================
MALLOC/FREE IN C++ (INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition:
malloc():
Allocates raw memory dynamically on the Heap.

free():
Releases memory allocated by malloc().

Header File:

#include <cstdlib>

=========================================================
SYNTAX
=========================================================

void* malloc(size_t size);

void free(void* ptr);

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

*ptr = 10;

cout << *ptr;

free(ptr);

=========================================================
MEMORY DIAGRAM
=========================================================

int* ptr = (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

Stack                    Heap
------                   ------
ptr ----------------->   [10]

ptr is on Stack.
Memory allocated by malloc() is on Heap.

=========================================================
ALLOCATING ARRAY
=========================================================

int n = 5;

int* arr =
    (int*)malloc(n * sizeof(int));

free(arr);

=========================================================
IMPORTANT
=========================================================

malloc()
• Only allocates raw memory.
• Does NOT initialize memory.
• Does NOT call constructors.

free()
• Releases memory.
• Does NOT call destructors.

=========================================================
UNINITIALIZED MEMORY
=========================================================

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

cout << *ptr;

Output:

Garbage Value

=========================================================
WHAT DOES malloc() DO INTERNALLY?
=========================================================

1. Allocates requested bytes.
2. Returns starting address.
3. Returns:

void*

No object construction.

=========================================================
WHAT DOES free() DO INTERNALLY?
=========================================================

1. Releases allocated memory.
2. Returns memory to Heap manager.

No destructor call.

=========================================================
WHY TYPE CAST IS REQUIRED IN C++?
=========================================================

malloc() returns:

void*

C:

int* ptr = malloc(sizeof(int));

Allowed.

C++:

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

Explicit cast required.

=========================================================
VERY IMPORTANT INTERVIEW EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Test
{
public:
    Test()
    {
        cout << "Constructor\n";
    }

    ~Test()
    {
        cout << "Destructor\n";
    }
};

int main()
{
    Test* ptr =
       (Test*)malloc(sizeof(Test));

    free(ptr);
}

Output:

No output.

Constructor and Destructor are NOT called.

=========================================================
NEW VERSION
=========================================================

Test* ptr = new Test();

delete ptr;

Output:

Constructor
Destructor

=========================================================
MEMORY LEAK
=========================================================

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

ptr = nullptr;

Memory lost.

Leak occurred.

=========================================================
CORRECT WAY
=========================================================

free(ptr);
ptr = nullptr;

=========================================================
DANGLING POINTER
=========================================================

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

free(ptr);

cout << *ptr;     // Undefined Behavior

Solution:

free(ptr);
ptr = nullptr;

=========================================================
MALLOC vs CALLOC
=========================================================

malloc()
---------
Allocates memory only.
Memory contains garbage values.

calloc()
---------
Allocates and initializes memory to zero.

Example:

int* arr =
(int*)calloc(5,sizeof(int));

Output:

0 0 0 0 0

=========================================================
MALLOC vs NEW
=========================================================

Feature              malloc()                new
------------------------------------------------------------------
Language             C                       C++
Return Type          void*                   Typed Pointer
Constructor Call     No                      Yes
Initialization       No                      Yes
Failure              Returns NULL            Throws bad_alloc
Operator/Function    Library Function        Operator
Deallocation         free()                  delete
Object Support       No                      Yes
Overloading          No                      Yes
Type Safety          Less                    More

=========================================================
MOST ASKED INTERVIEW QUESTION
=========================================================

Q:
Why should we avoid malloc() for C++ objects?

Answer:
Because malloc():

• Does not call constructors
• Returns raw memory only
• Does not initialize objects
• free() does not call destructors

Can lead to incomplete object initialization.

=========================================================
EXAMPLE
=========================================================

class Employee
{
    string name;
};

Employee* e =
   (Employee*)malloc(sizeof(Employee));

Undefined Behavior.

Reason:
string constructor not called.

Correct:

Employee* e = new Employee();

=========================================================
CAN WE MIX new/delete AND malloc/free?
=========================================================

NO.

Wrong:

int* ptr =
    (int*)malloc(sizeof(int));

delete ptr;

---------------------------------------------------------

int* ptr =
    new int;

free(ptr);

Both are:

Undefined Behavior.

=========================================================
CORRECT PAIRS
=========================================================

malloc()  ↔ free()

new        ↔ delete

new[]      ↔ delete[]

